<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a square of siding?", answer: "A 'square' in the siding and roofing trades equals 100 square feet. Siding is priced per square, and most products come packaged in partial squares — 2 squares per box of vinyl, 1 square per box of fiber cement lap, and so on. For a 2,000 sq ft wall area, you need 20 squares plus waste. Always order in whole squares to avoid ending up short on the last wall." },
  { question: "How do I measure wall area for siding?", answer: "Measure each wall length and multiply by wall height. Add gable areas as triangles (1/2 × base × height). Add up the totals for all walls. Subtract the area of windows (use 15 sq ft per standard window as a rule of thumb) and doors (21 sq ft for a standard entry door, 48 sq ft for a two-car garage door). Add 10 percent waste for cut-offs at corners and around openings." },
  { question: "How much waste for siding?", answer: "10 percent is standard for a rectangular house with typical window and door count. Add 15 percent for complex rooflines, multiple dormers, bay windows, or steep gables. Lap siding at corners (without J-channel or corner posts) wastes more than flat panels. Fiber cement trim and soffit are not counted in siding waste; order those separately." },
  { question: "Vinyl vs fiber cement siding cost?", answer: "Vinyl siding installed runs 5 to 12 dollars per square foot; fiber cement (like James Hardie) runs 8 to 15 dollars per square foot. For a 2,000 sq ft installation, vinyl is roughly 10,000 to 24,000 dollars, fiber cement 16,000 to 30,000 dollars. Fiber cement lasts longer (30 to 50 year warranty vs 20 to 30 for vinyl) but is heavier, harder to install, and needs repainting every 15 years. Vinyl is maintenance-free except for occasional washing." },
  { question: "Do I need to add separate siding for gables?", answer: "Yes. Gables are the triangular wall areas at the ends of a sloped roof. Their area is 1/2 × base × height. Add gables to the wall area. The calculator has a separate gable input so you can enter both and see the combined total. If the gable is very large or uses a different material, calculate it as a separate job." }
]) %>

